<DOC><DOCNO> AP890531-0088 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0959EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Waite     05-31 0263</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Britain-Waite,0271</SECOND><HEAD>Terry Waite's Family Marks His 50th Birthday Quietly</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The family of hostage Terry Waite, who turned 50today, said it was marking his birthday in quiet prayer for theChurch of England envoy.   ``Terry will obviously be even more in our thoughts today,''said his cousin, John Waite. ``I know hundreds of cards will bearriving, as they always do at times like these, from all over theworld.''   Waite, the archbishop of Canterbury's personal envoy,disappeared on Jan. 20, 1987, in Beirut, where he had been tryingto secure the release of foreign hostages. No group has claimed tohold him, but he is widely believed to be in Shiite Moslem hands.   ``As we go through our daily routines today, we will all besaying a prayer for Terry wherever he happens to be,'' John Waitesaid.   A spokesman for Archbishop Robert Runcie said: ``The archbishopwill be talking during the day with his (Waite's) brother and wife,but he is remembered every day in our prayers.'' The spokesman wasnot named according to British custom.   Waite's other brother, David, said the family believes Waitestill is alive.   ``Our faith takes the pressure out and we can relax in theknowledge that at the right time, Terry will be released,'' he said.   Terry Waite and his wife, Frances, have three daughters and oneson.   Fifteen foreigners, including nine Americans, are held bykidnappers in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry Anderson, chiefMiddle East correspondent of The Associated Press, who was takencaptive March 16, 1985.</TEXT></DOC>